      "evaluation_summary_text": "## Results\n\n### Empirical Strategy and Model Specification\n\nThis study employs Panel OLS with entity and time fixed effects to test the dual stratification hypothesis using data from 38 countries spanning the 1990-2023 period. The empirical strategy follows standard practice in comparative political economy for analyzing within-country variation in democratic quality (Acemoglu et al. 2008; Papaioannou and Siourounis 2008). By including country fixed effects, we difference out time-invariant country characteristics such as colonial heritage, geographic factors, and deep cultural norms that could confound the relationship between inequality and democratic quality. Time fixed effects control for common temporal shocks such as global economic crises, waves of democratization, and other period-specific factors affecting all countries.\n\nWe estimate four nested model specifications to systematically evaluate the dual stratification hypothesis:\n\n**Model 1 (Baseline)**: Includes the lagged depe...[truncated]"
